DNS spoofing tricks your device into visiting fake websites by sending false address info when you try to reach a real site. Instead of connecting to the right server, you're silently redirected to a malicious one—often looking the same. There, data can be stolen or malware installed. Attackers may hijack Wi-Fi, exploit router flaws, or poison caches. Even trusted URLs can be unsafe if DNS isn’t verified. Secure DNS, certificate pinning, and isolation help. Keywords like cache poisoning, DNSSEC, MITM, rogue gateway, and domain hijack lead deeper into why full disconnection breaks such chains.